03835nam a22005055i 9780773587410DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20112011xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735874107 a10.1515/97807735874102doi  a(DE-B1597)655991  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aNA746.N48.M45 2011eb 7aARC0050002bisacsh04a7201 aMellin, Robert, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNewfoundland Modern :bArchitecture in the Smallwood Years, 1949-1972 /cRobert Mellin. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b225 illustrations, colour throughout  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's/Beaverbrook Canadian Foundation Studies in Art History ;v700tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Illustrations -- tIntroduction -- tModernism Takes Hold -- tEarly Modernism -- tThe Formative Years of the NAA -- tModern Architecture in Canada’s Happy Province -- tPublic Health -- tHousing and Accommodation -- tPlaces of Worship -- tEducation and Recreation -- tIndustry and Commerce -- tFederal Public Works -- tProvincial and Municipal Public Works -- tTwo Newfoundland Architects -- tFrederick A. Colbourne -- tAngus J. Campbell -- tConclusion -- tHistory of the Founding of the NAA, 1958 -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn over 220 drawings and photographs, Robert Mellin presents the development of architecture in the decades immediately following Newfoundland's 1949 union with Canada. Newfoundland's wholehearted embrace of modern architecture in this era affected planning as well as the design of cultural facilities, commercial and public buildings, housing, recreation, educational facilities, and places of worship, and Premier Joseph Smallwood often relied on modern architecture to demonstrate the progress made by his administration. Mellin explores the links between Smallwood and modern architecture, revealing how Smallwood guided the development of numerous architectural projects. He also looks at the work of two innovative local architects, Frederick A. Colbourne and Angus J. Campbell, showing how their architecture was influenced by their life-long interest in art. The first comprehensive work on an important period of architectural development in urban and rural Newfoundland, Newfoundland Modern complements Mellin's award-winning book on the outport of Tilting, Fogo Island.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aArchitectszNewfoundland and LabradorvBiography. 0aArchitecturezNewfoundland and LabradorxHistoryy20th century. 0aModern movement (Architecture)zNewfoundland and Labrador. 7aARCHITECTURE / History / General.2bisacsh1 aRyan, William J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358741040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773587410423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773587410/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles